04621nam a22006495i 9780231554114DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212021nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315541147 a10.7312/mcbr201462doi  a(DE-B1597)612561  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPN1998.3.W56bM33 2021 7aPER0040102bisacsh04a791.4302/32092aB2231 aMcBride, Joseph, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBilly Wilder :bDancing on the Edge /cJoseph McBride. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource :b28 b&w figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aFilm and Culture Series00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tTHE PHANTOMS OF THE PAST -- tPictures -- t1 Ausländisch -- t2 “A Keen Observer” -- t3 “Film, That’s No Profession for Adults” -- t“WRITE SOME GOOD ONES” -- tPictures -- t4 “I Was Not in the Right Country” -- t5 Brackettandwilder . . . and Lubitsch -- t“ISN’T IT ROMANTIC?” -- tIntroduction -- t6 Dancing on the Edge -- t7 “Not a Funnyman but a Moralist” -- t8 “I Am No Longer Afraid” -- t9 “Tap- Dancing on the Grave of Hollywood” -- tFilmography -- tNotes on Sources -- tAcknowledgments and Influences -- tIndex -- tFILM AND CULTURE0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe director and cowriter of some of the world's most iconic films—including Double Indemnity, Sunset Blvd., Some Like It Hot, and The Apartment—Billy Wilder earned acclaim as American cinema's greatest social satirist. Though an influential fixture in Hollywood, Wilder always saw himself as an outsider. His worldview was shaped by his background in the Austro-Hungarian Empire and work as a journalist in Berlin during Hitler's rise to power, and his perspective as a Jewish refugee from Nazism lent his films a sense of the peril that could engulf any society.In this critical study, Joseph McBride offers new ways to understand Wilder's work, stretching from his days as a reporter and screenwriter in Europe to his distinguished as well as forgotten films as a Hollywood writer and his celebrated work as a writer-director. In contrast to the widespread view of Wilder as a hardened cynic, McBride reveals him to be a disappointed romantic. Wilder's experiences as an exile led him to mask his sensitivity beneath a veneer of wisecracking that made him a celebrated caustic wit. Amid the satirical barbs and exposure of social hypocrisies, Wilder’s films are marked by intense compassion and a profound understanding of the human condition.Mixing biographical insight with in-depth analysis of films from throughout Wilder's career as a screenwriter and director of comedy and drama, and drawing on McBride's interviews with the director and his collaborators, this book casts new light on the full range of Wilder's rich, complex, and distinctive vision.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aAustrianszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aJewszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aMotion picture producers and directorszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aMotion pictureszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / Direction & Production.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073907740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231554114423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231554114/original  a978-3-11-073907-7  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK